# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: stonehaven
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] The **A90 road** is a major north-to-south road in eastern Scotland, running from Edinburgh to Fraserburgh, through Dundee and Aberdeen.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] Along with the A9 and the A82 it is one of the three major north–south trunk roads connecting the Central Belt to northern destinations.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] The A90 is not continuous: there is a gap between Dalmeny and Perth, but the M90 connects those two places.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] The creation and development of the A90 road has to be understood in terms of the development of the economy of the North-East of Scotland, which had resulted in an increase in traffic along the route between Perth and Aberdeen.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] In recognition of this, in 1979, the British government announced that it was giving priority to the upgrading of the route to dual carriageway standard.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] It had already been decided that the trunk route between Dundee and Stonehaven, which had previously followed the same route as the railway line between the two towns, would now follow an inland route through Forfar and Laurencekirk.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] The coastal route from Dundee to Stonehaven was detrunked in 1978, at the same time as the inland route was trunked.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] In 1994, it was stated that £139 million had been spent since 1979 on upgrades to the then-A90 between Perth and Aberdeen (the section between Stonehaven and Aberdeen has since become part of the A92).
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] A grade-separated junction at Longforgan was opened in 1996.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] The section of the A90 between Balmedie and Tipperty was upgraded to dual carriageway in 2018.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] On 3 September 2018, the former section of the A90 between Stonehaven and Blackdog was renumbered A92 in preparation for the opening of the Aberdeen Western Peripheral Route, which became the new route of the A90.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] From Edinburgh, the A90 travels west and connects to the M90 motorway bypass route that leads to the M9: however, it is only possible to travel northbound when reaching this connection.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] After connecting with the M90, it runs as a short section of A-road before turning into the M90 properly at the Queensferry Crossing.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] At Perth, beneath Kinnoull Hill, the M90 again becomes the A90, now running north east to Dundee and through the Kingsway road system.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] It then passes Forfar, Brechin and Stracathro.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] The section of road previously part of the A90 was made part of the A92 and continues via Newtonhill, Portlethen, Cove Bay, the urban area of Aberdeen and the Bridge of Don before rejoining the A90 at Blackdog Junction, where the A'PRT terminates.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] Continuing north, the route crosses the Ythan Estuary near Ellon where it becomes a single carriageway, skirting Peterhead (and crossing Balmoor Bridge) on its way to Fraserburgh.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] The A952 road via Mintlaw is one of Aberdeenshire's principal freight routes.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] The Dundee to Aberdeen stretch of the A90 has many speed cameras.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] Previously, the 60-mile (97 km) trip from Dundee to Aberdeen along the A90 entailed over a dozen speed cameras including a majority of fixed Gatso types as well as locations used by mobile camera vans.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] These cameras were found on long fast stretches of road, and shortly before dangerous junctions, such as at the Laurencekirk junction where a 50 mph (80 km/h) speed limit is in force.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] This was introduced due to this junction's appalling safety record.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] A similar speed restriction was imposed at Forfar until two new grade-separated junctions were built, after which the restriction was lifted.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] In 2017 Average Speed Cameras were erected between Dundee and Stonehaven, with 15 per side, spaced approximately every 5 miles (8 km) for a total of 30 cameras.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] BBC News reported in January 2018 that speed limit compliance had increased from 2 in 5 to 99 in 100 drivers.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] A short stretch of the A90, from the southern terminus of the M90 to Barnton Junction (a junction with the A902), is part of Euroroute E15, which runs from Inverness to Algeciras in Spain.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] The E15 continues northwards on the M90, and southwards on the A902 leading to the Edinburgh City Bypass.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] The A90 ran along the coast and through Aberdeen until the city was bypassed with the opening of the Aberdeen Western Peripheral Route in 2018.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] The former stretch of A90 from Stonehaven through to just north of Aberdeen is now part of the A92.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] In January 2016 the Scottish Government announced £24 million for the design and construction of a new grade-separated junction at Laurencekirk on the A90.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] Ground investigations were carried out in 2019 in preparation for upgrading the flat junction between the A90 and the A937 to a flyover after a number of deaths.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] This followed years of local campaigning.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] However, in 2021 it was announced that work had been delayed.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] The proposed flyover would require the closure of a flat crossing at Oatyhill Farm which is now the sole access point to some properties after the nearby 170-year-old Oatyhill Bridge, which crosses the Dundee–Aberdeen line, was closed to road traffic in 2020.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] However, supplementary draft Orders and an Environmental Impact Assessment Report (Addendum) was published in December 2024 to facilitate the necessary works required at Oatyhill to allow the flyover to be built.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] Dualling of the section north of Aberdeen has been subject to studies since the 1980s.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] A proposal was published in 2007 for dualling the section between Balmedie and Tipperty.
[src:stonehaven/a90-road] While the Balmedie to Tipperty segment was eventually dualled as part of wider AWPR works, in 2023 the Scottish Government said it had no plans to dual the route north of Ellon.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The **A92** is a major road that runs through Fife, Dundee, Angus, Aberdeenshire, and Aberdeen City in Scotland.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] From south to north, it runs from Dunfermline to Blackdog, just north of Aberdeen.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The A92's original route in southern Fife is now numbered as the A921, following a largely coastal route through Burntisland and Kirkcaldy.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] It then headed north-west through Glenrothes and Cupar on the current route of the A91 and A914.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The former route connects with the M90 at Junction 1c via Burntisland and Kirkcaldy and links into the Thornton bypass.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The A92 acted as the main trunk road connecting Dundee to Aberdeen until the completion of the A90.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] Plans were drawn up in the 1960s for a new East Fife Regional Road starting at the M90 at the Masterton Interchange (Junction 2), which would have mirrored what is now the A921 and B9157 to the Mossgreen area, before heading north-eastward to Chapel Level, connecting up with the Thornton By-pass.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The plans were held back until the early 1970s, and were held back further due to the Oil crisis.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] Some of the original plans were for this new road to be a Motorway, but it was decided in the early 1980's to keep it as a high-quality dual carriageway.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] Fife Regional Council did the design for all the new sections of the East Fife Regional Road, with *Tractor Shovels Ltd* (later *Tractor Shovels Tawse Ltd* for the final two sections) carrying out the work.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] On 27 March 1998 the A92 was extended beyond the Crossgates junction to provide direct access with the M90 southbound, using south facing free-flow slip roads between M90 and A92 East Fife Regional Road, to ease congestion around the Halbeath interchange.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The new section had works beginning in August 1996, and was built three months ahead of schedule, costing £8.4m.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The Bankhead Roundabout, at the edge of Glenrothes, was built in 1993.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The junction is flared to allow for an A92 flyover to be built, but this has never been done.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] North of Glenrothes, from the New Inn Roundabout, to Forgan Roundabout near Woodhaven, the A914 and A92 road numbers were swapped in 1996, and thus completely bypassing Cupar.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The A92 now follows the dualled approach to the Tay Road Bridge, both opened in 1966.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] Prior to the opening of the Tay Road Bridge, the A92 continued along what is now the B995, along Cupar Road into Newport on Tay.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The A92 ended perpendicular to the River Tay when it reached the shoreline at Tay Street / High Street.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] Thus, traffic that was bound for the Tay Ferry and the rest of the A92 across the river therefore had to use a short section of the A914 to continue its journey.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The junction in Dundee with the B978 , near Claypotts Castle, was previously a roundabout, but was substantially rebuilt in the 1990s to provide a new dualled alignment for the A92 through the junction.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] From here to Arbroath, at the Elliot Roundabout, was dualled in 2005.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] In Arbroath, there is currently works to narrow the dual carriageway road, to provide more space for active travel options.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] Designed by Tayside Regional Council, and built by Torith Civil Engineering, the Inverkeilor bypass opened in 1989.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] There was also a straightening of the road at Hawkhill and Courthill bends, to avoid an accident blackspot near Lunan in 2012/2013.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The bridge over the South Esk at Montrose was replaced in December 2005, after it was deemed to be failing.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] In February 1997, the relief road for Montrose, taking traffic away from the town centre, was opened.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] There is a very short section of dual carriageway, about 1/4 of a mile long, built above Gourdon by Tractor Shovels, and opened in 1972.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The A92 formerly continued north from Stonehaven through Aberdeen, and terminated at Fraserburgh.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The section between Stonehaven and Aberdeen was renumbered A90 in 1994.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] Upon completion of the Aberdeen Western Peripheral Route (AWPR) in 2018, the section between Stonehaven and Blackdog was once again numbered as A92.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The section between Blackdog and Fraserburgh has now been renumbered A90 and A952.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The section of the A92 between Dundee and Aberdeen was formerly part of the Euroroute system, on route E120, a closed loop connecting Inverness, Aberdeen, Dundee and Perth.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] Starting at its junction with the M90 motorway, at the Halbeath Junction (junction 3 of the M90) on the east of Dunfermline, it runs north east past Cowdenbeath, Lochgelly, Kirkcaldy.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] From the Redhouse Roundabout, just north of Dysart, it heads in a much more northernly direction through Glenrothes, and then bypassing Freuchie, Ladybank and Newport-on-Tay.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] Again, it reverts to a single carriageway at the New Inn roundabout, just south of Freuchie, until a few miles short of the Tay Road Bridge at Dundee.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The section through Fife is often described as the East Fife Regional Road.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The road then travels across the Tay Road Bridge, the A92 travels along the south of Dundee, briefly merging with other roads.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] At the Scott Fyffe Roundabout in the Craigie area of Dundee, the road continues along the east coast bypassing Monifieth, Carnoustie and Muirdrum.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] When it reaches Arbroath, it becomes the main trunk road heading north along the coast.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] Skirting Inverkeilor, the road continues as the main trunk road through Montrose and St Cyrus, before skirting Benholm and Johnshaven.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] It then enters through Inverbervie, Roadside of Kinneff and Roadside of Catterline, before passing the Fowlsheugh Nature Reserve and then reaching the outskirts of Stonehaven where the road once again becomes dual carriageway.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] From here, the A92 runs parallel with the A90 for around 2 miles.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The road then continues past Stonehaven, Muchalls, Newtonhill, and Portlethen heading into the city of Aberdeen at the Bridge of Dee.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The road heads in a northernly direction through Aberdeen, to the west of the city centre.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] At Persley, it turns east, heading towards Bridge of Don.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] It then heads north for about three miles, before terminating at Blackdog, where the road once again merges with the A90.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The 16-mile section of the road from Dundee to Arbroath was upgraded to dual carriageway standard in 2005 and significantly improved both the safety of the route and the journey time between the two towns.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] Between Arbroath and Stonehaven the road is a single carriageway apart from a very short section of dual carriageway near Gourdon.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The road returns to dual carriageway from Stonehaven heading north to Aberdeen, briefly returning to single carriageway at the Bridge of Dee, and then again returning to single carriageway between the Haudagain and Parkway roundabouts in Aberdeen.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The remainder of the road from the Parkway roundabout to the termination point at Blackdog is dual carriageway.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] In 2024, work began to reduce the A92 within Arbroath to single-carriageway as part a remodelling that will see a dedicated cycle path and additional green space added.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] The A92 road traverses lands on which prehistorical archaeological sites are present.
[src:stonehaven/a92-road] Examples of these features include Gourdon Hill and the Stone of Morphie, both situated slightly to the west of the A92 alignment.
[src:stonehaven/ab-postcode-area] The **AB postcode area**, also known as the **Aberdeen postcode area**, is a group of 33 postcode districts in north-east Scotland, within 24 post towns.
[src:stonehaven/ab-postcode-area] Mail for the AB postcode area is processed at Aberdeen Mail Centre.
[src:stonehaven/ab-postcode-area] Originally, the area had only five postcode districts, AB1 to AB5.
[src:stonehaven/ab-postcode-area] In August 1990, these were recoded with the addition of second digits, such that every post town besides Aberdeen had its own district.
[src:stonehaven/ab-postcode-area] At the same time, IV33, IV34 and IV35 were recoded as part of AB38.
[src:stonehaven/aberchirder] 1204 as *Aberkerdour* means 'mouth of the Chirder'.
[src:stonehaven/aberchirder] It is formed from the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth' and the stream-name *Chirder* which is itself formed from the Gaelic words *ciar* 'dark, brown' and *dobhar* 'water'.
[src:stonehaven/aberchirder] This stream name is probably an adaptation of an earlier Pictish name.
[src:stonehaven/aberchirder] The village of Aberchirder was founded in 1764 by Alexander Gordon, the 5th Laird of Auchintoul.
[src:stonehaven/aberchirder] Until 1823 its official name was, in fact, Foggieloan after a small farm community on the site of which it was built.
[src:stonehaven/aberchirder] There is some uncertainty as to how the name Foggieloan originated.
[src:stonehaven/aberchirder] There are various theories; the most likely is that there is a stretch of moorland north of where the farm town existed (and, now, north of the village) which was named Foggieloan Moss from two Gaelic words *foidh* (peat moss) and *lòn* (meadow), so Foggieloan means peaty or boggy meadow.
[src:stonehaven/aberchirder] Kinnairdy Castle, now belonging to the Innes family is 2 miles to the south west, where the River Deveron joins the Auchintoul Burn.
[src:stonehaven/aberchirder] In 1823, the village is said to have been renamed 'Aberchirder' by the landowner, John Morison MP (later the 6th Baron of Bognie and Mountblairy), after the 13th century Thanes of Aberkerdour of Kinnairdy Castle.
[src:stonehaven/aberchirder] Alexander Gordon envisaged a thriving industrial village and built a small linen factory in Back Street (now North Street) which produced fine linen table-cloths and wincey using flax from Auchintoul Moss.
[src:stonehaven/aberchirder] By the late 19th century, wealthier inhabitants had built some grander houses and there was a selection of religious establishments throughout the town catering to various denominations in addition to the Church of Scotland and Free Church (1840, James Matthews) buildings.
[src:stonehaven/aberchirder] In 1960, the Royal Observer Corps opened a small monitoring bunker, to be used in the event of a nuclear attack.
[src:stonehaven/aberchirder] It was closed in 1991 and remains intact.
[src:stonehaven/aberchirder] The town is served by the 301 service between Huntly and Macduff, and the 303 between Huntly and Turriff.
[src:stonehaven/aberchirder] The town was formerly served by the 308 to Inverurie.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] In 1995, Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeen-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] The Aberdeenshire council area was created in 1996 under the Local Government etc.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] (Scotland) Act 1994, which abolished the regions and districts which had been created in 1975, replacing them with single-tier council areas.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] Aberdeenshire covered the area of the abolished Banff and Buchan, Gordon and Kincardine and Deeside districts, all of which had been part of the Grampian region.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] It is named after the historic county of Aberdeenshire, but covers a larger area, also including most of the historic county of Kincardineshire and eastern parts of the historic county of Banffshire.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] The council is the fifth largest Scottish council by number of councillors, having 70 members.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] The council has devolved power to six area committees: Banff and Buchan; Buchan; Formartine; Garioch; Marr; and Kincardine and Mearns.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] Each area committee takes decisions on local issues such as planning applications, and the split is meant to reflect the diverse circumstances of each area.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] Following the 2017 election a coalition of the Conservatives, Liberal Democrats and some of the independent councillors formed to run the council.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] The same parties continued running the council in coalition following the 2022 election.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] The first election to the council was held in 1995.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] It initially operated as a shadow authority alongside the outgoing authorities until the new system came into force on 1 April 1996.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] Aberdeenshire Council has been under no overall control since its creation.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] The role of provost is largely ceremonial in Aberdeenshire.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] They chair full council meetings and act as the council's civic figurehead.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] Political leadership is provided by the leader of the council.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] Of the independent councillors, seven form the 'Administration Independents' group, which forms part of the council's administration in coalition with the Conservatives and Liberal Democrats.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] Two Conservative councillors who defected to Reform UK in October 2024 were the party's first representatives in Scotland.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] The council is based at Woodhill House in Aberdeen, outside the council's own territory.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] The building was completed in 1977 for the former Grampian Regional Council.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] Since 2007 elections have been held every five years under the single transferable vote system, introduced by the Local Governance (Scotland) Act 2004.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire-council] Map of the area's ward (2017 configuration).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] It takes its name from the historic county of Aberdeenshire, which had substantially different boundaries.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] The Aberdeenshire Council area includes all of the areas of the historic counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire except the area making up Aberdeen City Council area, as well as part of Banffshire.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] The historic county boundaries are still officially used for a few purposes, namely land registration and lieutenancy.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire Council is headquartered at Woodhill House in Aberdeen, making it the only Scottish council whose headquarters are located outside its jurisdiction.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Aberdeen itself forms a different council area (Aberdeen City).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire borders onto Angus and Perth and Kinross to the south, Highland and Moray to the west and Aberdeen City to the east.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Traditionally, it has depended economically on the primary sector (agriculture, fishing, and forestry) and related processing industries.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Over the last 40 years, the development of the oil and gas industry and associated service sector has broadened Aberdeenshire's economic base, and contributed to a rapid population growth of some 50% since 1975.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Its land represents 8% of Scotland's overall territory.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] It covers an area of 6,313 square kilometres (2,437 sq mi).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire has a rich prehistoric and historical heritage.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] It is the locus of a large number of Neolithic and Bronze Age archaeological sites, including Longman Hill, Kempstone Hill, Catto Long Barrow and Cairn Lee.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] The area was settled in the Bronze Age by the Beaker culture, who arrived from the south around 2000–1800 BC.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Stone circles and cairns were constructed predominantly in this era.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Around the 1st century AD, the Taexali people, who left little history, were believed to have resided along the coast.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] The Picts were the next documented inhabitants of the area and were no later than 800–900 AD.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] The Romans also were in the area during this period, as they left signs at Kintore.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Christianity influenced the inhabitants early on, and there were Celtic monasteries at Old Deer and Monymusk.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Since medieval times, there have been many traditional paths that crossed the Mounth (a spur of mountainous land that extends from the higher inland range to the North Sea slightly north of Stonehaven) through present-day Aberdeenshire from the Scottish Lowlands to the Highlands.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Some of the most well known and historically important trackways are the Causey Mounth and Elsick Mounth.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire played an important role in the fighting between the Scottish dynasties.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] During the Anglo-Norman penetration, other families arrive, such as House of Balliol, Clan Bruce, and Clan Cumming (Comyn).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] During the Scottish Wars of Independence, the King of England Edward I travelled across the area twice with his invading army, in 1296 and 1303.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] In 1307, Robert the Bruce was victorious near Inverurie.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] These new families set the stage for the upcoming rivalries during the 14th and 15th centuries.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] This rivalry grew worse during and after the Protestant Reformation when religion was another reason for conflict between the clans.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] The Gordon family adhered to Catholicism and the Forbeses to Protestantism.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire was the historic seat of the clan Dempster.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Three universities were founded in the area prior to the 17th century, King's College in Old Aberdeen (1494), Marischal College in Aberdeen (1593), and the University of Fraserburgh (1592).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] During the 17th century, Aberdeenshire was the location of more fighting, centred on the Marquess of Montrose and the Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] This period also saw increased wealth due to the increase in trade with Germany, Poland, and the Low Countries.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] After the end of the Revolution of 1688, an extended peaceful period was interrupted only by fleeting events such as the Rising of 1715 and the Rising of 1745.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] The latter resulted in the end of the ascendancy of Episcopalianism and the feudal power of landowners.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] An era began of increased agricultural and industrial progress.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] The present council area is named after the historic county of Aberdeenshire, which has different boundaries and ceased to be used for local government purposes in 1975 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Local government functions were shared between the two levels.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] The modern council area was created in 1996 under the Local Government etc.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] It covers the combined area of the Banff and Buchan, Gordon, and Kincardine and Deeside districts that had been created in 1975.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] The present Aberdeenshire Council area therefore consists of all of the historic counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire (except the area of those two counties making up Aberdeen City), as well as the north-east portions of Banffshire.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] The population of the council area has risen over 50% since 1971 to approximately 265,080 in 2024, representing 4.7% of Scotland's total.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's population has increased by 9.1% since 2001, while Scotland's total population grew by 3.8%.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] The census lists a relatively high proportion of under 16s and slightly fewer working-age people compared with the Scottish average.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire is one of the most homogeneous/indigenous regions of the UK.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] In 2011, 82.2% of residents identified as 'White Scottish', followed by 12.3% who are 'White British', whilst ethnic minorities constitute only 0.9% of the population.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] The largest ethnic minority group is Asian Scottish/British at 0.8%.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] In addition to the English language, 48.8% of residents reported being able to speak and understand the Scots language.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 256,382 residents aged three and over, 121,797 (47.5%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] This is the greatest proportion of Scots speakers of any Scottish council area.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 256,377 residents aged three and over, 3,579 (1.4%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's Gross Domestic Product (GDP) is estimated at £3,496M (2011), representing 5.2% of the Scottish total.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's economy is closely linked to Aberdeen City's (GDP £7,906M), and in 2011, the region as a whole was calculated to contribute 16.8% of Scotland's GDP.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Between 2012 and 2014, the combined Aberdeenshire and Aberdeen City economic forecast GDP growth rate is 8.6%, the highest growth rate of any local council area in the UK and above the Scottish rate of 4.8%.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] A significant proportion of Aberdeenshire's working residents commute to Aberdeen City for work, varying from 11.5% from Fraserburgh to 65% from Westhill.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Average Gross Weekly Earnings (for full-time employees employed in workplaces in Aberdeenshire in 2011) are £572.60.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] This is lower than the Scottish average by £2.10 and a fall of 2.6% on the 2010 figure.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] The average gross weekly pay of people resident in Aberdeenshire is much higher, at £741.90, as many people commute out of Aberdeenshire, principally into Aberdeen City.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Total employment (excluding farm data) in Aberdeenshire is estimated at 93,700 employees (Business Register and Employment Survey 2009).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] The majority of employees work within the service sector, predominantly in public administration, education and health.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Almost 19% of employment is within the public sector.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's economy remains closely linked to Aberdeen City's and the North Sea oil industry, with many employees in oil-related jobs.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] The average monthly unemployment (claimant count) rate for Aberdeenshire in 2011 was 1.5%.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] This is lower than the average rate of Aberdeen City (2.3%), Scotland (4.2%) and the UK (3.8%).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] In the 2014 Scottish independence referendum, Aberdeenshire voted 'No' by a percentage of 60.4%.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] In the 2016 European Union membership referendum, Aberdeenshire voted 'Remain' by the third lowest margin of 55.0%.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] First and second lowest margin for 'Remain' were Moray (50.1%) and Dumfries and Galloway (53.1%).
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] There are numerous rivers and burns in Aberdeenshire, including Cowie Water, Carron Water, Burn of Muchalls, River Dee, River Don, River Ury, River Ythan, Water of Feugh, Burn of Myrehouse, Laeca Burn and Luther Water.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Numerous bays and estuaries are found along the seacoast of Aberdeenshire, including Banff Bay, Ythan Estuary, Stonehaven Bay and Thornyhive Bay.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire has a marine west coast climate on the Köppen climate classification.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire is in the rain shadow of the Grampians, therefore it has a generally dry climate for a maritime region, with portions of the coast receiving 25 inches (64 cm) of moisture annually.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Summers are mild, and winters are typically cold in Aberdeenshire; Coastal temperatures are moderated by the North Sea such that coastal areas are typically cooler in the summer and warmer in the winter than inland locations.
[src:stonehaven/aberdeenshire] Coastal areas are also subject to haar, or coastal fog.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Stonehaven was formerly the county town of Kincardineshire, succeeding the now abandoned town of Kincardine.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] It is currently administered as part of Aberdeenshire.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The town is known in the local Doric dialect as *Steenhive* (Scots pronunciation: [stinˈhɑev] ⓘ) and is nicknamed *Stoney*.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Stonehaven is the site of prehistoric events evidenced by finds at Fetteresso Castle and Neolithic pottery excavations from the Spurryhillock area.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] In 2004, archaeological work by CFA Archaeology, in advance of the building of the Aberdeen to Lochside Natural Gas Pipeline, found two short cists burials containing cremated remains to the southwest of Stonehaven.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Radiocarbon dating put the burials in the first half of the 2nd millennium BC, which was the Early Bronze Age in Scotland.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The burials contained stone tool artifacts and shale/cannel coal beads.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] That same year, researchers at the National Museums of Scotland and Yale University announced that a fossil found by an amateur paleontologist the previous year was the earliest known fossil of a land-dwelling animal.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The fossil was about 420 million years old.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The town lies at the southern origin of the ancient Causey Mounth trackway, which was built on high ground to make passable this only available medieval route from coastal points south of Aberdeen.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] This ancient passage specifically connected the Bridge of Dee to Cowie Castle via the Portlethen Moss and the Stonehaven central plaza.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The route was taken by the Earl Marischal and Marquess of Montrose when they led a Covenanter army of over 9,000 men in the first battle of the Wars of the Three Kingdoms in 1639.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The Covenanters were imprisoned in Dunnottar Castle, where many died.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] A memorial to them can be found in Dunnottar Church.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Other castles in the vicinity are Fetteresso Castle and Muchalls Castle, both of which are in private ownership and not open to the public.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The oldest surviving structure in Stonehaven is the Stonehaven Tolbooth at the harbour, used as an early prison and now a museum.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Dunnottar Castle, perched atop a rocky outcrop, was home to the Keith family, and during the Scottish Wars of Independence, the Scottish Crown Jewels were hidden there.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] In 1296 King Edward I of England took the castle, only for William Wallace to reclaim it in 1297, burning down the church in the process with the entire English garrison still in it.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] In 1650, Oliver Cromwell sacked the castle to find the Crown Jewels following an eight-month siege (having previously destroyed the English Crown Jewels).
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] However, just before the castle fell, the Crown Jewels were smuggled out by some ladies who took them by boat to a small church just down the coast in the village of Kinneff, where they remained undetected for eleven years.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Stonehaven was a Jacobite town in the Fifteen and it was a safe base for the retreating Jacobite army to stay overnight on the night of 5–6 February 1716.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] In the Forty-Five Stonehaven, part of the Episcopalian north-east, was again ‘reliably Jacobite’ and it was one of the north-eastern ports where reinforcements, plus money and equipment were periodically landed from France.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] After 1709, when Dunnottar Parish Church was taken over by the Church of Scotland Episcopalian services were held in the tolbooth until a meeting house was built in the High Street in 1738.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Following the failure of the Forty-Five, the Duke of Cumberland ordered the building to be demolished.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Services were then held in a house on the High Street.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Stonehaven Town Hall, which is an events venue in the town, was completed in 1878.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Near the Cowie Bridge, at the north of Stonehaven, was a fishing village known as Cowie, which has now been subsumed into Stonehaven.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Somewhat further north are the ruins of Cowie Castle.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Slightly to the west of Stonehaven is the ruined Ury House, originally a property of the Frasers.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] A fossil of the oldest known land animal, *Pneumodesmus newmani*, a species of millipede, was found at Stonehaven's Cowie Beach in 2004.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Stonehaven is 15 miles (24 km) south of Aberdeen sheltered in Stonehaven Bay.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The Carron Water and Cowie Water run through the town.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Stonehaven lies adjacent to a deeply indented bay surrounded on three sides by higher land between Downie Point and Garron Point.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] At the western edge of Stonehaven west of the A90 road lies the village of Kirkton of Fetteresso.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Nearby to the south, Fowlsheugh is a coastal nature reserve, known for its 230-foot-high cliff formations and habitat supporting prolific seabird nesting colonies.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Stonehaven has grown rapidly since the oil boom in Aberdeen.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The increasing demand for new, middle-class housing has seen four new estates being appended to the town, creating an expanse of suburbs and Stonehaven has been bypassed since 1984.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Parts of Stonehaven near to the Carron Water were prone to flooding following heavy rain.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Aberdeenshire Council has completed construction of flood defenses in 2023 that have now been effective at preventing flooding from major storms.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The Highland Boundary Fault traverses Scotland from the Isle of Arran and Helensburgh on the west coast to immediately north of Stonehaven on the east coast.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The largest park is Mineralwell, situated adjacent to the Glenury Viaduct which carries the Dundee–Aberdeen line.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] St Kieran's Well, a grade-C listed public fountain, is situated in the park.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] It was restored in 1982, though its water supply has since been severed.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The park contains one of the largest purpose built radio controlled car circuits in the UK, located at the edge of the park beside the viaduct.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The John McRobert Pavilion was opened in the park in 1993 and an artificial turf pitch opened in the park in 2015.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] In 2021, 120 cherry blossom trees were planted as part of the Sakura Cherry Tree Project.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The trees are dedicated to Thomas Blake Glover.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Nearby Baird Park occupies an area of four acres and was given to the town by Sir Alexander Baird in 1920, though it had been leased to the council for the previous twelve years.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Stonehaven Recreation Grounds was opened in 1885 and is situated near the beach.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] It contains tennis courts and a bowling green.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Dunnottar Woods is a 32.91-hectare (81.3-acre) woodland area managed by the Woodland Trust.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The town has a secondary school, Mackie Academy, which was founded at the site occupied currently by Arduthie School.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The feeder primary schools include: Glenbervie, Inverbervie, Lairhillock, Gourdon, Catterline, Kinneff, Arduthie, Mill’o forest, Dunnottar and Carronhill.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] One special education school, Carronhill, opened in 1975.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] It is situated in the newer part of the town near Mill O' Forest Primary School.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Historically the chief commerce of Stonehaven lay in fishing.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Led by the herring fishery, the catch peaked around the year 1894 with a peak catch of about 15 million fish per annum and employment in the fishing industry of 1280 people.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Due to overfishing to serve the expanding regional population, the fishing industry declined with diminishing catches, such that by 1939 only a remnant of the earlier fishing fleet continued to exist, and the catch mostly supported the local population from that point onward.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Glenury distillery was situated near Mineralwell park, and closed in 1985.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Currently, the town's primary industries are marine services and tourism, with Dunnottar Castle, a local landmark, bringing in a large number of tourists every year.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Dunnottar Castle is regularly used in promotional material by the Scottish tourism industry; in addition, it was used in the 1990 film *Hamlet*, and appeared as a featured desktop background in the UK edition of Microsoft Windows 7.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Furthermore, Dunnottar Castle was also selected as Merida's home in the Disney movie, Brave.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Situated nearby is Stonehaven War Memorial, constructed after World War I.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] It was unveiled by Viscountess Cowdray in 1923.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] It is visible from much of the town thanks to its prominent position on a hilltop overlooking the bay.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Another attractive feature of the town is the long beach facing the North Sea, with large cliffs at either end sheltering small rock pools and inlets.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] It is also famous for its Olympic-size outdoor swimming pool, which is heated and filled with filtered seawater.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The local harbour features the Tolbooth, the town's small museum of local heritage.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] During Hogmanay festivities, crowds watch the annual fireballs ceremony in which volunteers walk down the High Street swinging their fireball - a homemade ball of burning waste materials with a chain and handle attached.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The Fireball Festival was part of the content of STV's Hogmanay coverage.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The fireballs are finally thrown into the harbour.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] It is uncertain when the fireballs began, however, reports covering the event from as early as 1911 exist.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The event has taken place annually, though has been cancelled during the world wars and in 2021 due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Stonehaven's long-established pipe band plays at events throughout the year, including the folks festival and fireball ceremony.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The band has competed at various levels throughout its illustrious history including several years at the prestigious Grade 1.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] In 1906 the new breakwater was nearing completion, and in the Annual Report of the Fishery Board for Scotland the hope was expressed that it would encourage the fishermen to acquire steam drifters.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The Second Edition Six inch Ordnance Survey Map of Stonehaven shows the town at about this time,including the breakwater.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Unfortunately, as the statistics show, the decline of the town as a fishing port continued.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The town's Haven Fish Bar was the likely origin of the deep-fried Mars Bar, a snack now culturally associated with Scotland - and its health record - as a whole.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] In 2012, the (since renamed) Carron fish and chip shop sold around 100–150 deep-fried Mars bars per week, with tourists accounting for around 70% of this figure.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The Carron was awarded No 1 Fish and Chip Shop in Scotland 2020.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Another local fish and chip shop, the Bay, was awarded the number one fish and chip shop in Scotland, at the National fish and Chip awards in 2012 and 2013.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Every July, Stonehaven holds a Highland Games.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] All those competing in the heavy events (which include the Hammer, the Heavy Stone, and Tossing the Caber) must wear full Highland dress.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Other events include the Stonehaven Folk Festival, regularly attended by famous Glaswegian comedian Billy Connolly.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] On the first Saturday in June, the Feein' Market recreates a 19th-century agricultural hiring fair.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The RW Thomson Classic Car Rally is an annual celebration of the inventor of the pneumatic tire and attracts an impressive range of vintage and classic cars.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] There are two harbour festivals each summer.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] A farmers' market is now held once a month in the market square, where local food suppliers and producers can sell fresh fruit, vegetables, poultry, and other types of meat.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Stonehaven supports a rugby club - Mackie Academy Former Pupils Rugby Football Club - which plays in the RBS Caledonia Regional League Division 1.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] They have previously trained on pitches at Red Cloak.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The town has a Junior football club - Stonehaven F.C. - that plays in the North Region Scottish Junior Football North Premier League.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Home games are played at Glenury Park, set in Mineralwell Park.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] There are also three amateur football clubs: AC Mill Inn, Cowie Thistle and Stonehaven Athletic, as well as Stonehaven Youth Football Club, who all play their games in Mineralwell Park.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The Local Community Radio Station Mearns FM broadcasts to the town and surrounding area, including Inverbervie and Laurencekirk.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Staffed completely by volunteers, it is run as a not-for-profit organisation, broadcasting under a community radio license, with a remit to provide locally focused news, events, and programming.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Jointly funded by local adverts and local and national grants, Mearns FM has one of the largest listening areas of any community radio station owing to the Mearns' distributed population.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Stonehaven was the birthplace of Robert William Thomson, inventor of the pneumatic tyre.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] It is also the birthplace of James Murdoch, a journalist and Orientalist, Lord Reith of Stonehaven, the first Director-General of the BBC, and Tom McEwen, a Canadian communist politician and trade union organiser.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] John Ellis, an architect who was born and lived here, was responsible for many local buildings including the War Memorial.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] George Thomson Chapman (1824–1881), a New Zealand publisher, was born in Stonehaven.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Ury House, Stonehaven, is the ancestral seat of the Viscounts Stonehaven.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] It was built by Sir Alexander Baird, 1st Baronet in 1885.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The novelist Lewis Grassic Gibbon (James Leslie Mitchell) attended school at what was the old Mackie Academy (now Arduthie Primary).
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Famous historical visitors include William Wallace and Mary, Queen of Scots.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Poet Robert Burns met friends in Stonehaven in 1787.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The town has been served by Stonehaven railway station on the Dundee–Aberdeen line since 1849.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Initially located outside the town, it has been absorbed by the growing town.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The A90 road bypasses the town and meets the A92 here.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] The town has a local service and is also on the X7 Coastrider route between Aberdeen and Dundee.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] A locally run Land Train runs from the town square to the outdoor pool, Dunnottar Castle and the harbour.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Woodcot Hospital operated from 1867 to 1998.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Kincardine Community Hospital continues to operate today.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] On 11 June 2013 it was decided by the Justice Committee that Stonehaven Sheriff Court would be closed despite a petition attracting nearly 300 signatures and disagreement from the local community.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Lifeboats were provided by the local charity Maritime Rescue Institute until its closure in 2013.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] A Royal National Lifeboat Institution station was subsequently established.
[src:stonehaven/stonehaven] Stonehaven Leisure Centre was opened in 1985 following an investment of £650,000 and contains sports halls and a 25-metre swimming pool.
